{{Infobox video game |title = Neopets: Petpet Adventures: The Wand of Wishing |image = Petpetadventures PSPBox.jpg |developer = [[SCE Santa Monica Studio]] |publisher = [[Sony Computer Entertainment]] |artist = Scott Butler |designer = |engine = |released = {{vgrelease|NA|March 14, 2006}} |genre = [[Action game|Third-person action]] |modes = [[Single-player]] |platforms = [[PlayStation Portable]] }}
'''''Neopets: Petpet Adventures: The Wand of Wishing''''' is an [[Action game|action]] video game, released on March 14, 2006. It is a single-player [[PlayStation Portable]] action/adventure game based on the [[Neopets]] franchise.<ref>{{cite web|author=US Playstation|date=2005-05-14|url=http://www.us.playstation.com/NeopetsPetpetAdventures/ |title=Neopets Petpet Adventures |publisher=US Playstation|accessdate=2007-03-25 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070318125522/http://www.us.playstation.com/NeopetsPetpetAdventures/ |archivedate = March 18, 2007}}</ref>
==Gameplay== There are four playable Petpets: Doglefox, Krawk, Mazzew, and Meowclops. Throughout the game, the player can acquire items such as swords, staves, wands, magic spells, and armor for the head and body. It can then be customized with the items. As an [[anthropomorphic]] Petpet from Neopia, the player must find and utilize various items. There is no experience or leveling up to improve the petpet. Instead, tokens have to be won by paying a fee and challenging bosses in the Battledome. Once a player has the correct token for a particular statistic, it then can be used at a trainer. Also available in the Battledome is a wireless feature where a player's Petpet can fight his friends'. If [[Wireless ad hoc network|Ad Hoc]] multiplayer is used, the entrance fee is removed and the winner still receives the token corresponding to the battledome challenged in.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}
==Plot== The game takes place in the hidden [[Petpet]] world of Petaria, in which the player must retrieve the magical "Wand of Wishing" in order to succeed as a warrior.
==Reception== IGN praised the game for its cute protagonists and outdoing typical expectations of a franchise game. However, there is criticism of imbalance, such as the difficulty when starting off and the overpowering bows that can be acquired.<ref>{{cite web|author=IGN|date=2006-03-24|url=http://psp.ign.com/articles/698/698384p1.html |title=The Wand of Wishing Review |publisher=IGN |accessdate=2008-05-12}}</ref>
