{{Infobox person | name = Regina Amollo | birth_date = 1954 | birth_place = Uganda | occupation = Writer | notable_works = A Season of Mirth, When Mother Leaves Home, The Pain of Borrowing }}
'''Regina Amollo''' (born {{circa|1954}}) is a Ugandan writer.<ref name="odeke">{{cite news | url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/new_vision/news/1313094/amollo-quit-nursing-educate-people-writing | title=Amollo quit nursing to educate her people through writing | work=New Vision | date=23 January 2013 | accessdate=15 May 2016 | author=Odeke, Steven}}</ref>
Trained as a nurse, Amollo started writing her first novel, ''[[A Season of Mirth]]'', in 1976.<ref name="odeke"/><ref name="nabiruma">{{cite news | url=http://www.observer.ug/component/content/article?id=9152:one-manuscripts-23-year-journey | title=One manuscript‚Äôs 23-year journey | work=The Observer | date=5 July 2010 | accessdate=15 May 2016 | author=Nabiruma, Diana}}</ref> She was encouraged to complete the manuscript by one of her professors, Austin Ejiet, but it took until 1999 for the book to be published.<ref name="nabiruma"/> The book, which explores male chauvinism and women's oppression in Uganda,<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rMnkcZsv_eEC&pg=PA38&lpg=PA38 | title=Culture and Customs of Uganda | publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group | author=Otiso, Kefa M. | year=2006 | pages=38 | isbn=9780313331480}}</ref> is now required reading for Ugandan students.<ref name="nabiruma"/>
Amollo retired from nursing in 2009.<ref name="odeke"/> She has published several other books, including ''When Mother Leaves Home'' and ''The Pain of Borrowing''.<ref name="odeke"/><ref name="nabiruma"/> She wrote a two volume primer for the [[Kumam dialect|Kumam]] language, ''Pwonyo Isoma Itabu Me Agege,'' and published an anthology of stories by women writers entitled ''Those Days in Iganga''.<ref name="nabiruma"/>
