{{Infobox officeholder | name=Salibi al-Zahir | image= | caption= | reign= | office1=[[Multazem]] of [[Tiberias]] | term_start1=1750s | term_end1=1773 | predecessor1=[[Zahir al-Umar]] | successor1=Ahmad al-Zahir | dynasty=[[Ottoman Empire]] | parents=Zahir al-Umar | spouse= | children= |relations=[[Al-Zayadina|Zaydani family]] | birth_date= | birth_place= | death_date=1773 | death_place=[[Nile Delta]], [[Egypt Eyalet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] | place of burial= | religion=[[Sunni Islam]] |}} '''Salibi al-Zahir''' (given name also spelled ''Sulaybi'' or ''Celebi'') (died 1773) was the ''[[mutasallim|multazem]]'' ([[tax farm]]er) of [[Tiberias]] in the mid-18th century, during the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] rule. He was appointed to the post by his father, [[Zahir al-Umar]], the virtually autonomous ruler northern [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]].<ref>Philipp, 2013, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=95I5QVdp4_gC&pg=PA153 153]</ref> He was Zahir's eldest son and generally known to be his most loyal son. However, he did join his brothers Uthman, Ahmad and Sa'id in a rebellion against their father, in which they were defeated.<ref>Joudah, 1987, p. 51.</ref>
Salibi led a contingent of Zahir's troops to support [[Ali Bey al-Kabir]]'s bid to regain control of [[Egypt Eyalet|Egypt]] from [[Abu al-Dhahab]]. However, Salibi and Ali Bey's troops were decisively defeated and Salibi was killed in battle.<ref>{{Citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N78KAQAAMAAJ&q=Sulaybi+Zahir&dq=Sulaybi+Zahir&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCIQ6AEwAWoVChMIysX-w_7vxgIVQZyACh1LEwAg|title=Middle East Forum|volume=48|publisher=Alumni Association of the American University of Beirut|year=1972}}</ref> Zahir was distressed by the death of his son and upon hearing the news, he collapsed to the ground and exclaimed "From this day I am undone".<ref>Sabbagh, 2008, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=8CAzGKXK6acC&pg=PP22 41]</ref> Salibi was succeeded by his brother Ahmad al-Zahir as ''multazem'' of Tiberias.<ref>Joudah, 1987, p. 127.</ref>
